0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDrawing on international case studies from emerging economies and developing countries including South Africa, India, Egypt, Morocco, Jordan, Tunisia, Indonesia, China and Russia, this book examines the rise, nature and effectiveness of recent developments in social policy in the Global South. By analysing these new emerging trends, the book aims to understand how they can contribute to meaningful change and whether they could offer alternative solutions to the social, economic and environmental policy challenges facing low-income countries within a contemporary global context. It pays particular attention to reforms and innovations relating to the objectives of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development, including the move away from a welfare state, towards a ‘welfare multitude’, in which new actors, such as civil society organisations, play an increasingly important role in social policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aAgarwala, Rina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChung, Heejung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Linda J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFang, Lijie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaagh, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalasa-Rappel, Yara A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHu, Bo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIarskaia-Smirnova, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaasch, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/